animation

Tutorial this is based on found here: https://jtr13.github.io/cc21fall2/how-to-animate-your-plots.html

Read in the data file

df <- read_csv("pop_by_age.csv")
## Rows: 77805 Columns: 4
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (2): Age, Name
## dbl (2): Year, Population
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.

Reorder Age

df$Age <- factor(df$Age, levels = c("0-4", "5-9", "10-14", "15-19", "20-24", "25-29", "30-34", "35-39", "40-44", "45-49", "50-54", "55-59", "60-64", "65-69", "70-74", "75-79", "80-84", "85-89", "90-94", "95-99", "100+"))

#specify Year as an integer 
df$Year<- as.integer(df$Year) #this fixes an issue when labeling the graphs with a date

Static plot

df %>%
  filter(Name == "Afghanistan") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Age, y = Population)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + 
  labs(title = paste("Afghanistan population"), y = "Population", x = "Age") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Animated plot!

df %>%
  filter(Name == "Afghanistan") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Age, y = Population)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + 
  transition_time(Year) + #just add this part for an animation!
  labs(title = paste("Afghanistan population in {frame_time}"), y = "Population", x = "Age") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Animated plots!

df %>%
  filter(Name == "Afghanistan" | Name == "Iran") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Age, y = Population)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') + 
  transition_time(Year) + #just add this part for an animation!
  labs(title = paste("Population in {frame_time}"), y = "Population", x = "Age") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))+
  facet_wrap(vars(Name))
